[{"id":43506,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["A is false but R&nbsp;is true","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true but R&nbsp;is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R&nbsp;is false","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true and R&nbsp;is the correct explanation of A"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In reverse bias condition of photodiode, the change in saturation reverse current is directly proportional to the change in the incident light flux or light intensity, which can be measured accurately. It is not so when photodiode is forward bias.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43500,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66ace8b9-40df-4e1c-9f03-3fc224c3affc-9895337_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 329px; height: 130px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4cd5f92-274c-4a47-932a-a780c6955a61-9895337_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 320px; height: 110px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d185e4eb-07fe-4574-a70a-fb4cc4367ddf-9895337_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 292px; height: 140px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40f85be9-fe91-4c1a-a883-e2962f6829c0-9895337_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 287px; height: 130px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In the given logical circuit, all logic gates are NAND gate.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e6d63d7a-44fc-4bbd-9aaf-ddea76954c38-9895337.PNG\" style=\"width: 369px; height: 125px;\" /></p><p>Here, the inputs&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;are inverted using NOT gate (made using NAND gate), then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></math>&nbsp;are applied as inputs in other NAND gate.</p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>A</mi></menclose></mfenced><mo>=</mo><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi></menclose></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>B</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>B</mi></menclose><mo>=</mo><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>B</mi></menclose></math></p><p>Output at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi></menclose><mo>.</mo><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>B</mi></menclose></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></math>.</p><p>The above boolean expression is for OR gate.</p><p>Truth table of OR gate is&nbsp;</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 300px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>The output waveform is shown below.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40f85be9-fe91-4c1a-a883-e2962f6829c0-9895337_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 287px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43552,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OR</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AND</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NOR</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NAND</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/130b696d-8a5c-4ce1-90a8-178e7c259c02-image.png\" style=\"width: 335px; height: 145px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43468,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{A}=0, \\mathrm{~B}=0, \\mathrm{C}=0, \\mathrm{D}=1$","$\\mathrm{A}=0, \\mathrm{~B}=1, \\mathrm{C}=1, \\mathrm{D}=1$","$\\mathrm{A}=1, \\mathrm{~B}=0, \\mathrm{C}=0, \\mathrm{D}=0$","$\\mathrm{A}=1, \\mathrm{~B}=1, \\mathrm{C}=1, \\mathrm{D}=0$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Bulb will glow if bulb have potential drop on it. One end of bulb must be at high (1) and other must be at low (0).\nOption (3) satisfy this condition\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DEpomuw8j6JG8zgonzwiPEQy2DscwpWNNxVe75qAYUU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43645,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["NAND gate","OR gate","NOR gate","AND gate"],"answer":1,"solution":"When either of $A$ or $B$ is 1 i.e. closed then lamp will glow.\nIn this case, Truth table\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qKEYQetW2pzGC-zs5e0RE1894iOsQmrZu22ucdCFlKA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":43627,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Solar cell, Light dependent resistance, Zener diode, Simple diode","Zener diode, Solar cell, Simple diode, Light dependent resistance","Simple diode, Zener diode, Solar cell, Light dependent resistance","Zener diode, Simple diode, Light dependent resistance, Solar cell"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/587582d2-4d72-40cf-9093-7aa70a82aeef-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 195px;\" /><br />Graph represents V-I characteristics of simple diode.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d6749a4-9c7e-49c6-8556-e5402959cf86-image.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 201px;\" /><br />Graph represents V-I characteristic of Zener diode.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/73190b6a-6512-4739-9dbb-824a25d81105-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 193px;\" /><br />Graph represents V-I characteristics of Solar cell&nbsp;<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/85d8722f-15c1-4ec5-9d08-d21f4c930363-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 181px;\" /><br />Graph represents V-I characteristics of light dependence resistance.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":43574,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["lightly doped and have narrow depletion layer.","heavily doped and have wide depletion layer.","lightly doped and have wide depletion layer.","heavily doped and have narrow depletion layer."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Zener breakdown occurs in a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>n</mi></math> junction having <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp;both because ,&nbsp;zener breakdown occurs in the heavily doped p-n junction diode. Heavily doped <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> junction diodes have narrow depletion region.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43660,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\pi}{4}$","$\\pi$","$0$","$\\frac{\\pi}{2}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No phase difference between input and output signal","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":43647,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["OR gate","NOT gate","XOR gate","NAND gate"],"answer":0,"solution":"Truth table for given combination is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xE3LWrUM6RelXiU8PEuJRu5vd1pNbKCbYnD-7sk9ciM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nThis comes out to be truth table of OR gate","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":43497,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The doping level of collector is intermediate between the heavy doping of emitter and the light doping of the base. The doping level and width of base are kept light so that most of the charge carriers are transferred from emitter to collector without much recombination.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43430,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$Y = 1101$","$Y = 0010$","$Y = 0111$","$Y = 1000$"],"answer":0,"solution":"From the given logic circuit, the input $A$ passes through a NOT gate, giving $\\overline{A}$.<br><br>This output $\\overline{A}$ and the input $B$ are then fed into a NAND gate.<br><br>The Boolean expression for the final output $Y$ is:<br>$Y = \\overline{\\overline{A} \\cdot B}$<br><br>Given the $4$-bit binary inputs:<br>$A = 1101$<br>$B = 1010$<br><br>First, find the bitwise NOT of $A$:<br>$\\overline{A} = \\overline{1101} = 0010$<br><br>Next, find the bitwise AND of $\\overline{A}$ and $B$:<br>$\\overline{A} \\cdot B = 0010 \\cdot 1010 = 0010$<br><br>Finally, apply the NOT operation for the NAND gate:<br>$Y = \\overline{0010} = 1101$<br><br>Alternatively, using De Morgan's laws:<br>$Y = \\overline{\\overline{A} \\cdot B} = A + \\overline{B}$<br>$Y = 1101 + \\overline{1010} = 1101 + 0101 = 1101$<br><br>Therefore, the output $Y$ is $1101$.<br><br>Answer: $Y = 1101$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43568,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>654</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math> and red colour","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>654</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math> and orange colour","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1046</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math> and red colour","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1046</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math> and blue colour"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>E</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>654</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math></p><p>Red color</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43474,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efa50f0a-54c8-4ccb-b9c9-b7f1f26f0729.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 179px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/863fecd0-e5a7-4373-96bd-824fca4226d7.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 185px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3e1e598-b9e6-4a2b-9e33-694fdb24f0ca.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 169px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7df38dad-0f02-4bdf-8dab-1df738674fd9.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 174px;\"/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/075453a4-6492-415f-8a60-966a9962fe1e.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 181px;\"/></p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>;</mo><mo> </mo><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>;</mo><mo> </mo><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>;</mo><mo> </mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>;</mo><mover><mrow><mo> </mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p>Using De Morgan's theorem, we can write </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mover><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mover><mfenced><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mover><mfenced><mrow><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>¯</mo></mover><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>·</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>·</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43448,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_vJDFNNG0eg1SGZx5pN4hzZbNZQSVILbTBf_VxQ7yu8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dyTilMlp8LBu2-8XH2pH-CQS7fznuFYltFenz5XCZGc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/T9svxTwNbCrUYwi4SAQa_9jQHijh6L8VWoMHxpDuxqY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vGWvwXOQq0gOFzdSCm5B9Sb3pSwXPoaMYhl3sS-tTls.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Only option (2) matches with the truth table","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43649,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ntpgErNsubb_zOBpikO4vWX01rghNV3bQEEBFKvvWgA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TBURl2fTDgm7l82f0_AYUi8eOnQSjWvN_KRZ0fcaMT0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tESMNALJBL9fYXc40wcYsswAbUiLbpE_2yfs1hK_6jY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QF37ngM6LH__n76EIxHVp7pHkCNbfbIu9DI8zyiwI9U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Truth Table\n\\begin{array}{|l|l|l|}\n\\hlineA & B & Y \\\\\n\\hline 1 & 1 & 1 \\\\\n\\hline 1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\n\\hline 0 & 1 & 0 \\\\\n\\hline 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Qo_K0pTSyAgy7Lazzmc92YmqEsD-3yvVNgRZe4cfFAI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":43586,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d794763f-3cac-4c85-b54f-27c6f6267792-image.png\" style=\"width: 385px; height: 135px;\" /></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 300px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">A</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">B</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi></menclose></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></menclose></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi></menclose></mfenced><mo>.</mo><mfenced><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></menclose></mfenced></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi></menclose></mfenced></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>Q</mi></menclose><mo>=</mo><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>z</mi></menclose></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">0</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43633,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Base, emitter and collector","Base, collector and emitter","Emitter, base and collector","Collector, emitter and base"],"answer":1,"solution":"Now, according to the question, A lead of the transistor is connected to the positive lead of the ammeter and the ammeter gives a deflection. We know that in an n-p-n transistor, the emitter and the collector are negatively doped, while the base is positively doped. So, in this type of transistor the electric field is from the base to the other terminals. Thus, the lead A must be the base of the transistor.<br />Now, the lead C is connected to the negative lead of the ammeter. Also, the leads B and C are connected by moist fingers. So, some conduction is there in between these two terminals. Therefore, both the emitter and the collector are connected to the negative end of the terminal. But the moist fingers are less conductive than the lead. So the lead B is not directly connected to the negative end.<br />We are having a large deflection in the ammeter. This means that there is a huge amount of current from the base to the other terminal. This is possible only when the terminal adjacent to the base terminal has a high number of charge carriers. As the emitter is most highly doped, so the lead C must correspond to the emitter.<br />Now the only terminal left for the third lead B is the collector. So, the lead B must be the collector.<br />Thus, A is the Base, B is the collector, and C is the emitter.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43642,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["NAND gate","NOR gate","AND gate","OR gate"],"answer":2,"solution":"Truth table is as shown :\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/drdI-lbMa6zltZr5JUeqvm-VLocVVbmTahgRsDyTuzA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nThus the combination of two NOT gates and one NOR gate is equivalent to a AND gate.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":43624,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&alpha;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&beta;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&beta;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math> <msup> <mi>α</mi> &nbsp;</msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">α</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">β</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&alpha;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&beta;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&beta;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;<br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>&#8733;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>&#8733;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":43543,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Cut-off region only","Saturation region only","The active region only","Both cut-off and Saturation"],"answer":2,"solution":"Active region of the CE transistor is linear region and is best suited for its use as an amplifier.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43548,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Statement I&nbsp;is false but Statement II is true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true."],"answer":1,"solution":"Pentavalent material has excess free <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;because we mix the impurities like phosphorus and arsenic having five electrons in the outermost shell. So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>density increases, but overall semiconductor is neutral. So we can say that&nbsp;Statement I is true but, Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43453,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{AB}}$ would be zero at all times","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nfgosFWrTC5JlgymP4pgm61Na-jKLdMwJW8WKLPbSCo.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/psVBiWklYsuLMjVeozLus4ezpIHpl4M7o6jOQUy9yjw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m3w26ehAWUDQ1tz-7r8GdDSyGOlSDqzZVX5nVkqgYHc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{V}=\\mathrm{V}_0 \\sin \\omega \\mathrm{t}$\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/NW1F5kttZbDyex6FTbHA8l8TX1EDYD2LBf7WDBeCCx0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43611,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\beta \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}, \\frac{\\Delta I_E}{\\Delta I_B}, \\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}$","$\\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}, \\frac{\\Delta I_C}{\\Delta I_B}, \\beta \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}$","$\\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}, \\frac{\\Delta I_C}{\\Delta I_E}, \\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}$","$\\beta \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}, \\frac{\\Delta I_C}{\\Delta I_B}, \\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Current gain $\\beta=\\frac{\\Delta I_C}{I_B}$\nVoltage gain $\\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{v}}=$ Current gain $\\times$ Resistance gain $=\\beta \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}$\nPower gain $A_p=(\\text { Current gain })^2 \\times$ Resistance gain\n$$\n=\\beta^2 \\frac{R_L}{R_{B E}}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":43654,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\frac{4}{7}$","$\\frac{5}{8}$","$\\frac{4}{5}$","$\\frac{5}{4}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\frac{\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{e}}}{\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{n}}}=\\frac{7}{5} \\frac{\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{e}}}{\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{n}}}=\\frac{7}{4}$\n$\\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{d}}\\right)_{\\mathrm{e}}}{\\left(\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{d}}\\right)_{\\mathrm{n}}} \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{e}}}{\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{n}}} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{n}}}{\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{e}}}=\\frac{5}{4}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":43551,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">e</mi></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">h</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">e</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><msub><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">h</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>16</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>22</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>32</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>22</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>9</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43554,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b91cb447-5427-4cd7-851a-3be7e131d972-image.png\" style=\"width: 433px; height: 192px;\" /></p><p>Voltage across,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">L</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p><p>Also, voltage across <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn></math> volt</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">i</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mrow><mn>90</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Current in zener diode is maximum when&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"\"><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"\"><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>So&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mrow><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43445,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["(A), (C), (D) only","(A), (C), (E) only","(A), (B), (E) only","(A), (B), (C) only"],"answer":2,"solution":"(A) n type semiconductor holes are minority carriers and $\\mathrm{e}^{-}$are majority carriers<br/>(B) Dopant are pentavalent atom.<br/>(C) $\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{e}} \\cdot \\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{h}}=\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{i}}^2$ for intrinsic semiconductor<br/>(E) In $n$ type semiconductor primary source of holes generation are thermal excitation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43572,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>~</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>~</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>~</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>~</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b06873b4-4fcf-4135-a6f3-70fec01715ad-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 188px;\" /></p><p>Here only <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> will work and we know for silicon diode, potential drop on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43472,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>21</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given: Threshold wavelength <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>660</mn><mo> </mo><mi>nm</mi></math>.</p><p>Therefore, energy required(or band gap energy) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>λ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>660</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>660</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p>So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43658,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$1.33 \\mathrm{~A}$","$1.71 \\mathrm{~A}$","$2.00 \\mathrm{~A}$","$2.31 \\mathrm{~A}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$D_1$ is reverse biased therefore it will act like an open circuit.\n$$\n\\mathrm{i}=\\frac{12}{6}=2.00 \\mathrm{~A}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":43475,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["NAND","NOR","OR","AND"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a17d19de-7fa5-4721-bcfd-1ea7d866daa5.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 123px;\"/></p><p>From De-Morgan's law we can write:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mover><mrow><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>A</mi></menclose><mo>·</mo><menclose notation=\"top\"><mi>B</mi></menclose></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mover><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43639,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["A NAND B","A OR B","AAND B","ANOR B"],"answer":0,"solution":"The output at $\\mathrm{C}$ corresponds to A NAND\n$$\n\\mathrm{B} \\text { or } \\overline{\\mathrm{A} \\cdot \\mathrm{B}}=\\mathrm{C}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43503,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and statement II are incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but statement II is correct","Both Statement I and statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but statement II is incorrect"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Doping silicon with boron leads to holes without any additional&nbsp;electron. This results in P-type semiconductors.&nbsp;Arsenic is pentavalent therefore when added with silicon it leaves one electron as a free electron. This results in N-type semiconductors.&nbsp;</p><p>When such P-type and N-type semiconductors are fused to make a junction,&nbsp;an electric field is produced from the N-side to the P-side, causing a barrier potential to develop.&nbsp;Because of the barrier potential, the majority of charge carriers are unable to flow through the junction, hence current is zero,&nbsp;unless we apply forward bias voltage. We cannot detect the current through ammeter as battery is not connected.</p><p>Hence, statement I is correct but statement II is incorrect.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43618,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math><mi>R</mi><mo>~</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mi>R</mi><mo>~</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></math>","<math><mi>R</mi><mo>~</mo><mn>0.1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1.0</mn></math>","<math><mi>R</mi><mo>~</mo><mn>0.1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0.01</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The input resistance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;of a transistor is in the range of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>k&#937;</mi></math>.</p><p>The output resistance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;of a transistor is in the order&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>k&#937;</mi></math>.</p><p>So, the ratio of output resistance and input resistance,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>k&#937;</mi></mrow><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>k&#937;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>~</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43464,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["$\\Lambda \\cdot B(\\Lambda+B)$","0","$\\overline{\\mathrm{A}} \\cdot \\mathrm{B}$","$A \\cdot B$"],"answer":1,"solution":"By truth table\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ET6SXCdB2mlRd4f42uFxEHcbm-zPD3sKhPbqXqwQa8g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null}]